Integrating Vuex with a Vue.js application involves a few steps:

Step 1: Install Vuex
---------------------
You can install Vuex using npm or yarn.
```
npm install vuex --save
```
```
yarn add vuex
```

Step 2: Create a Vuex Store
----------------------------
Create a new directory inside your src folder called "store". Inside the "store" folder, create a new file called "index.js". This file will hold your Vuex store definition.

```
import Vue from 'vue'
import Vuex from 'vuex'

Vue.use(Vuex)

const store = new Vuex.Store({
  state: {
    // state properties
  },
  mutations: {
    // mutations
  },
  getters: {
    // getters
  },
  actions: {
    // actions
  },
})

export default store
```

Step 3: Mount the Vuex Store to your Vue.js Application
--------------------------------------------------------
Go to the entry file of your application (most likely main.js). Import the created Vuex store and import it into your Vue instance.

```
import Vue from 'vue'
import App from './App.vue'
import store from './store'

new Vue({
  el: '#app',
  store,
  render: h => h(App)
})
```

Step 4: Use the Vuex Store Data Inside your Vue Components
-----------------------------------------------------------
You can use Vuex store data in your Vue components using `computed` properties, `mapGetters` and `mapActions` functions.

Example:
```
<template>
  <div>
    <h2>{{ message }}</h2>
    <button @click="increment">Increment</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import { mapGetters, mapActions } from 'vuex'

export default {
  computed: {
    ...mapGetters([
      'message'
    ])
  },
  methods: {
    ...mapActions([
      'increment'
    ])
  }
}
</script>
```
In the above example, `message` is a getter property defined in the Vuex store and `increment` is an action method defined in the Vuex store.
